JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 199
EP  - 223
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.70004
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT We highlight the role of economic materialism as a cultural phenomenon of significance in relation to economic transformation and development. By inducing material aspirations, an endogenous cultural change toward more widespread adherence to materialistic values is both a cause and an effect of productivity growth. This cultural?economic complementarity is a powerful mechanism of endogenous productivity growth; it also determines the prevalence of different cultural values vis-à-vis the prominence of material objectives. From a historical perspective, the model draws attention to a novel mechanism through which cultural change may have contributed to the take-off toward sustained economic growth.
ER  - 

